commit_message:
Build enablerepo options automatically for leapp when not subsribed.

A new option added into leapp lets us configure a set of repositories to run
leapp with. This new option is compatible with rhos-release, removing the need
for an special leapp actor.
This patch checks the rhos-release repos configured locally in the Undercloud
and builds a --enablerepo string with all the repos obtained. This string is
then passed at the time of running leapp, if the machine isn't using a
subscription.

This patch also cleans up some unnecessary code to handle differente leapp
versions, as our CI now works with latest leapp version. As well as some
unsupported Leapp environment variables [0].

[0]-https://github.com/oamg/leapp/blob/69f3f8c21dae5fbe270701e5728b8e2512faddb6/docs/source/el7toel8/envars.md

Change-Id: Ife2734547c4c981dece0c0f9b436eb10e99dd1b1
(cherry picked from commit d067ed4b22a7e221d62767dd6d30e2d7fd07d294)

commit_message:
Simplify ffwd2 CIP stein parameters.

Currently, the ContainerImagePrepare parameters required for FFWD2
to work are harcoded in the defaults/main.yaml. However, the
namespace_stein variable, should point at the same value the namespace
variable points. This patch simplifies a little the logic, adds a new
fact full_namespace that stores the content of the namespace field from
the containers-prepare-parameters.yaml file and assigns the namespace_stein
key to it.

Change-Id: I07967e0590aee9c86a6427469914f65fbdb3929d
(cherry picked from commit cdce7a9cb6aed9f6659515e827a47873f856edaf)

After a quick look, I personaly love your proposed changes, I can easily imagine some use cases which can use retrying patterns with that for some reasons. 

By example using tenacity [1] and retry on error, see the example bellow.

Example on the customer side where retrying is needed:
```
from tenacity import *
from oslo_messaging.exceptions import MessageUndeliverable

@retry(retry=retry_if_exception_type(MessageUndeliverable))
def call(transport, target, number):
    client = oslo_messaging.RPCClient(transport, target, options={'mandatory': True})

    for i in range(1, 50):
        time.sleep(3)
        r = client.call({}, 'foo', id_value=str(i), test_value="hello oslo")
        print("hello" + r + " - number: " + str(number))
```

I need to do more tests and review it more deeply but globally I really love it :)

I put a simple +1 for now to notice that I appreciate your changes even if it still WIP.

[1] https://github.com/jd/tenacity'}, {'account_id': 19298, 'date': '2019-05-29 11:15:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

I haven't tested this, but conceptually I really like the idea."}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2019-05-29 14:15:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

In any case, +1 to this behavior. Still waiting on one of our messaging folks to comment, but I think they were onboard with this as well. Note that the WIP will need to be removed before this merges, and obviously the unit test failures will need to be fixed."}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2019-05-29 14:18:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Oh, one other thing: What impact does this have on the driver interface? This option is specific to rabbit, will the other drivers need to start taking an "options" parameter too that will be ignored? Either way I guess we'll need to document what options a given driver accepts.'}, {'account_id': 29364, 'date': '2019-05-29 14:32:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thanks Ben,
RabbitMQ by default _does not raise any exception_ if the message is not routed. 
You can test the mandatory flag in kombu following this example:
https://github.com/celery/kombu/issues/1039

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 28522, 'date': '2019-06-12 12:52:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 8770, 'date': '2019-06-12 14:06:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

I like this addition to the API, however I do have two concerns I'd like to see addressed - more about policy than the code itself:

The term 'options' is pretty generic and I think it can lead to confusion when introducing new parameters to the send API.  Specifically when do I add something to "options" vs when a new keyword parameter is warranted?  Why isn't "retry" an option and 'mandatory' is? etc.

I think we need to clarify what we consider "options" and what we consider "things added to the parameter list".

For example - not necessarily a good one, but an example:

1) Generic RPC concepts - timeout, retry (hmm), etc, are keyword parameters
2) we use the keyword "delivery_options" or "delivery_flags" (blah) that affect the quality of service for the message delivery itself ('confirm-receipt', 'at-most-once', 'at-least-once', etc).

Which brings me to my second concern - what if a transport does NOT support a given option?  For example the term 'mandatory' is rabbit specific - the AMQP ISO standard does not implement a 'mandatory' flag.  And I don't know enough about Kafka's protocol either way.'}, {'account_id': 8770, 'date': '2019-06-12 14:30:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

Sorry for the comment bombing :(

I wanted to point out that it was my suggestion to Gabriele to add an options parameter to send in order to make the 'mandatory' flag optional.

My concern was that if we simply turned on 'mandatory' then we've introduced a new behavior and that things would break.

However after reading Sean's comments I may have been wrong with that approach.

I think it can be argued that - in some cases - use of 'mandatory' should be, well, _mandatory_.  Here's my thoughts:

o.m. supports 3 flavors of RPC calls:

a 'call' - blocks for a reply
a 'cast' - simple send no reply expected
a 'fanout cast' - a cast, but the message is broadcast to all subscribers

I think that 'mandatory' should be turned on by default for the 'call' case.  It should be an option (default off) in the cast/fanout case.

Right now IIRC when o.m. does a 'call' it sends the request message then blocks for the reply until timeout even if there is no consumer for the request.  What 'mandatory' would do in this case is to fail immediately if there is no consumer rather than time out (Gabriele correct me if I'm wrong).  

That's a good thing, right?  In fact I'd say that it is a bug _not_ to use the mandatory flag in the 'call' case.

Options?"}, {'account_id': 29364, 'date': '2019-06-14 08:31:15.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 11.'}, {'account_id': 29364, 'date': '2019-06-14 08:37:21.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 12.'}, {'account_id': 28522, 'date': '2019-06-14 11:19:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12:

commit_message:
Add transport_options parameter

With this new parameter is possible to pass other parameters
from the client to the drivers.
So it is possible to tune the driver behavior.

For example can be used to send the mandatory flag in RabbitMQ

Note:
  - The transport_options parameter is not actually used (yet).
  - This part of blueprint transport-options  (first part)

Implements: blueprint transport-options
The blueprint link is
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo.messaging/+spec/transport-options

Change-Id: Iff23a9344c2c87259cf36b0d14c0a9fc075a2a72

EC2 token requests contain a signature that signs the entire request,
including the access timestamp. While the signature is checked, the
timestamp is not, and so these signed requests remain valid

commit_message:
Check timestamp of signed EC2 token request

EC2 token requests contain a signature that signs the entire request,
including the access timestamp. While the signature is checked, the
timestamp is not, and so these signed requests remain valid
indefinitely, leaving the token API vulnerable to replay attacks. This
change introduces a configurable TTL for signed token requests and
ensures that the timestamp is actually validated against it.

The check will work for either an AWS Signature v1/v2 'Timestamp'
parameter[1] or the AWS Signature v4 'X-Aws-Date' header or
parameter[2].

commit_message:
Remove requirements-integration job

This job was a legacy job that attempted to verify each project could be
independently installed after all global-requirements had been
installed.

This job is no longer necessary since we have much better coverage with
requirements-check and other jobs that make sure the requirements are
compatible. It is also a legacy zuulv2 job, uses the long deprecated
devstack-gate, and runs with Python 2.7.

For historical reference, this was added originally to PBR back in 2013
[0] and moved to requirements in 2014 [1].

[0] https://opendev.org/openstack/pbr/commit/378261a8cba818a29b7e3d33b917de5ed0751579
[1] https://opendev.org/openstack/requirements/commit/8e073738db06086f949d2be377999356aee2d8d0

Change-Id: I29abcba929995f9307c392110160d889a29b47c3
Signed-off-by: Sean McGinnis <sean.mcginnis@gmail.com>
(cherry picked from commit 58d622019d8e92b301699787180aafe16cde53ee)
Signed-off-by: Matthew Thode <mthode@mthode.org>
(cherry picked from commit 442891e31e28bbc430be722ba50058ceda9e2308)

commit_message:
[NetApp] Fix driver to honor standard extra specs

During migration and manage/unmanage operations, if we used standard
extra_specs format (e.g. 'thin_provisioning'='True') instead of
NetApp based extra_specs format (e.g. 'netapp:thin_provisioned'='True'),
NetApp driver used to ignore these standard extra_specs settings
and continued the operation with the default option.
The driver is now fixed to handle this issue by honouring the
standard extra_specs during migration and manage/unmanage.

Change-Id: I48f4d966201fc8d6bd6eec0c37f1575b434310e7
Closes-Bug: #1707084
(cherry picked from commit 9250e02b56fa4a0d93fe4c32cdfac4eceab8d095)
(cherry picked from commit 678ea79f85e53ec21a0fb74758875b3a7ebe1aa7)
(cherry picked from commit 644e2cfc564208bd5b9b3e1201f8f9718ca65823)

commit_message:
Support new Rhel Enforcement in CI.

Starting from 16.0, OSP, the Red Hat version of tripleo, enforce
certain rules between Rhel version and OSP version.

Those checks rely on the Red Hat subscription mechanism.

To support CI when no subscription is apply we need to disable the
enforcement.  This is done by setting SkipRhelEnforcement to True.

So we add code here to disable the check by default for CI.

The new option --enforce-rhel set to yes make it possible to run the
update while keeping the enforcement to test subscribed environment.

Change-Id: Idac7c370aaaed2805787c0b3327bb9b7e91f1561
(cherry picked from commit 7dd448c566a460e06f8c355771bdc280c5dd265b)

commit_message:
Fix the amphora noop driver

The amphora no-op driver did not get updated properly for the multi-amphora
failover fix.
This patch fixes that issue and corrects the doc strings for the
haproxy amphora driver update_amphora_listeners method.

Change-Id: Ib0d63da7c5599069f5ea50f0dfbc59eefba58c84
(cherry picked from commit c8074cd18a8c6ccdae7a490c8e9615acc2cadaf4)

commit_message:
Support notification/polling full config by hiera

The existing YAML templates for pipeline, event_pipeline and
polling configurations aren't flexible enough to support more
complex setups.

This commit adds support for allowing the whole YAML config to be
defined in Hiera by adding some new class arguments.

Change-Id: If08d876d659871f02f3ccfd9f20ccb3605f98de1

commit_message:
r10k: Replace removed env parameters by options

The environment parameters, PUPPETFILE_DIR and PUPPETFILE is no longer
valid in r10k command, so should be replaced by options, --moduledir
and --puppetfile[1].

[1] https://github.com/puppetlabs/r10k/commit/ea477d4729a7895e5f7d4ae4a41ac0f8f0eda1c9

Change-Id: Ic50a93d87c3187219700632bf221b7bcf29ca92f

commit_message:
Revert deleted config section in Swift config files

A recent commit [1] removed config sections related to logging that
causes various Swift services to fail to start. This patch reverts the
respective config sections. These may be removed at a later date.

[1] https://review.opendev.org/#/c/671711/

Change-Id: Ie73811e36f1ea35f060cb5af4e1275e7e69d4179

commit_message:
Add a job to run a standalone deploy with IPA on multinode

This review adds the job:
tripleo-ci-centos-8-standalone-on-multinode-ipa
to create a multinode setup of two nodes.

The IPA server is set up on the secondary node
and a standalone deployment - using the IPA server
is run on the primary node.

Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/720757
Story: https://tree.taiga.io/project/tripleo-ci-board/us/670
Change-Id: I69f016eccdfffdb5a896447c02011b6ee0a02185

commit_message:
Federated openid support using auth_mod_openidc

This patch adds support for using mod_auth_openidc instead of shibboleth for
supporting users who have a preference to use oidc for federation. A new
variable called apache_mod is added to keystone_sp allowing the auth library
to be selected. If left undefined shibboleth auth module will continue to be
installed by default maintaining backward compatibility.

This patch does not support simultaneous use of shibboleth and mod_auth_openidc
primarily because shib2 depends on libcurl3 but mod_auth_openidc depends on
libcurl4 which cannot coexist on Ubuntu. This can be resolved when there is a
shib3 package available in a future release of Ubuntu.

Change-Id: I80031f7d3f0fcc2029cd6861dcb6687e8a9f0a2e
(cherry picked from commit 47fe909d544935fe8c648c410f6b3cdb3f6216bf)

commit_message:
Return empty list instead of None for tags

commit_message:
ceph: run handlers after common

When you're running ceph-install with upgrade_ceph_packages, the
packages get upgraded in the ceph-common, but some services aren't
getting restarted to account for the new version.

According to ceph-ansible/site.yml.sample, the order is ceph-common
applied to all hosts, then later in the "hosts: mons" or "hosts: osd"
the handlers get applied, after ceph-facts and before ceph-config.

Change-Id: I3e95b7fad6eda9f689287efe16c35418a9e7e561
(cherry picked from commit e42b2898c6a7d8bf503a96853a737b8fa4f112d7)

commit_message:
[devstack][ci] Move bgp setup to plugin

We currently use a legacy devstack-gate script
to create the bgp speaker, and peer required
to communicate to and from the tenant private
IPv6 networks.

Move this logic to the devstack plugin so that
we can invoke it automatically with the existing
devstack variable MANILA_SETUP_IPV6.

Change-Id: Iea90e3f04ae05e5783c3163bbf2d2dabd128c7b5
(cherry picked from commit 2277c20c02641c3a0cd0804ef53a54cd5492ce2d)

[{'created': '2020-05-07 22:15:45.000000000', 'message': "[devstack][ci] Modify firewall in ds-plugin

To set up some first party backends such as
ZFSOnLinux, CephFS via NFS gateway, Container
(where the NAS server is containerized) and LVM,
manila's devstack plugin creates a NAS server
on the devstack host.

On test machines, access to this NAS server is
firewalled from networks outside of the host's
internal network namespace (including from private
project networks that are in different network
namespaces, on the same devstack host).

We currently use a legacy devstack-gate script
to disable firewall on NFS ports; however,
anyone that installs devstack with LVM, Container,
ZFSOnLinux, CephFS-NFS drivers will need these
firewall ports to be opened to be able to mount
shares exported off their devstack host machines.

Move these firewall commands to the devstack plugin.
These commands can be invoked by setting the localrc
variable MANILA_ALLOW_NAS_SERVER_PORTS_ON_HOST to True.
The value of this variable is False by default,
to preserve existing behavior.

Change-Id: Ic9cad47662f1edf2e5c710dbe64d580bc5f01d44
(cherry picked from commit 36b1715e86919a739d3639f9c0d2c80e9f853e7a)
(cherry picked from commit 94486eb4c09ac64f0e7cdf34945a84b11c1b0ae0)
"}]
commit_message:
[devstack][ci] Modify firewall in ds-plugin

To set up some first party backends such as
ZFSOnLinux, CephFS via NFS gateway, Container
(where the NAS server is containerized) and LVM,
manila's devstack plugin creates a NAS server
on the devstack host.

On test machines, access to this NAS server is
firewalled from networks outside of the host's
internal network namespace (including from private
project networks that are in different network
namespaces, on the same devstack host).

We currently use a legacy devstack-gate script
to disable firewall on NFS ports; however,
anyone that installs devstack with LVM, Container,
ZFSOnLinux, CephFS-NFS drivers will need these
firewall ports to be opened to be able to mount
shares exported off their devstack host machines.

Move these firewall commands to the devstack plugin.
These commands can be invoked by setting the localrc
variable MANILA_ALLOW_NAS_SERVER_PORTS_ON_HOST to True.
The value of this variable is False by default,
to preserve existing behavior.

Change-Id: Ic9cad47662f1edf2e5c710dbe64d580bc5f01d44
(cherry picked from commit 36b1715e86919a739d3639f9c0d2c80e9f853e7a)
(cherry picked from commit 94486eb4c09ac64f0e7cdf34945a84b11c1b0ae0)

revisions:
[{'created': '2020-05-06 15:18:36.000000000', 'message': "Fix security issues with EC2 credentials

This change addresses several issues in the creation and use of EC2/S3
credentials with keystone tokens.

1. Disable altering credential owner attributes or metadata

Without this patch, an authenticated user can create an EC2 credential
for themself for a project they have a role on, then update the
credential to target a user and project completely unrelated to them. In
the worst case, this could be the admin user and a project the admin
user has a role assignment on. A token granted for an altered credential
like this would allow the user to masquerade as the victim user. This
patch ensures that when updating a credential, the new form of the
credential is one the acting user has access to: if the system admin
user is changing the credential, the new user ID or project ID could be
anything, but regular users may only change the credential to be one
that they still own.

Relatedly, when a user uses an application credential or a trust to
create an EC2 credential, keystone automatically adds the trust ID or
application credential ID as metadata in the EC2 access blob so that it
knows how the token can be scoped when it is used. Without this patch, a
user who has created a credential in this way can update the access blob
to remove or alter this metadata and escalate their privileges to be
fully authorized for the trustor's, application credential creator's, or
OAuth1 access token authorizor's privileges on the project. This patch
fixes the issue by simply disallowing updates to keystone-controlled
metadata in the credential.

2. Respect token roles when creating EC2 credentials

Without this patch, a trustee, an application credential user, or an
OAuth1 access token holder could create an EC2 credential or an
application credential using any roles the trustor, application
credential creator, or access token authorizor had on the project,
regardless of whether the creator had delegated only a limited subset of
roles. This was because the trust_id attribute of the EC2 access blob
was ignored, and no metadata for the application credential or access
token was recorded either. This change ensures that the access
delegation resource is recorded in the metadata of the EC2 credential
when created and passed to the token provider when used for
authentication so that the token provider can look up the correct roles
for the request.

Conflicts (six removal in  e2d83ae9, pep8 fixes in e2d83ae9):
      keystone/api/credentials.py
      keystone/tests/unit/test_v3_application_credential.py
      keystone/tests/unit/test_v3_credential.py

Change-Id: I39d0d705839fbe31ac518ac9a82959e108cb7c1d
Closes-bug: #1872733
Closes-bug: #1872755
Closes-bug: #1872735
(cherry picked from commit 37e9907a176dad6843819b1bec4946c3aecc4548)
(cherry picked from commit 2f2736ebb267c757ad77fcf25ee0aaeefab2a09d)
(cherry picked from commit 27caafe3daa552663719954f2cd6713dd4493178)

commit_message:
Fix security issues with EC2 credentials

This change addresses several issues in the creation and use of EC2/S3
credentials with keystone tokens.

1. Disable altering credential owner attributes or metadata

Without this patch, an authenticated user can create an EC2 credential
for themself for a project they have a role on, then update the
credential to target a user and project completely unrelated to them. In
the worst case, this could be the admin user and a project the admin
user has a role assignment on. A token granted for an altered credential
like this would allow the user to masquerade as the victim user. This
patch ensures that when updating a credential, the new form of the
credential is one the acting user has access to: if the system admin
user is changing the credential, the new user ID or project ID could be
anything, but regular users may only change the credential to be one
that they still own.

Relatedly, when a user uses an application credential or a trust to
create an EC2 credential, keystone automatically adds the trust ID or
application credential ID as metadata in the EC2 access blob so that it
knows how the token can be scoped when it is used. Without this patch, a
user who has created a credential in this way can update the access blob
to remove or alter this metadata and escalate their privileges to be
fully authorized for the trustor's, application credential creator's, or
OAuth1 access token authorizor's privileges on the project. This patch
fixes the issue by simply disallowing updates to keystone-controlled
metadata in the credential.

2. Respect token roles when creating EC2 credentials

Without this patch, a trustee, an application credential user, or an
OAuth1 access token holder could create an EC2 credential or an
application credential using any roles the trustor, application
credential creator, or access token authorizor had on the project,
regardless of whether the creator had delegated only a limited subset of
roles. This was because the trust_id attribute of the EC2 access blob
was ignored, and no metadata for the application credential or access
token was recorded either. This change ensures that the access
delegation resource is recorded in the metadata of the EC2 credential
when created and passed to the token provider when used for
authentication so that the token provider can look up the correct roles
for the request.

Conflicts (six removal in  e2d83ae9, pep8 fixes in e2d83ae9):
      keystone/api/credentials.py
      keystone/tests/unit/test_v3_application_credential.py
      keystone/tests/unit/test_v3_credential.py

Change-Id: I39d0d705839fbe31ac518ac9a82959e108cb7c1d
Closes-bug: #1872733
Closes-bug: #1872755
Closes-bug: #1872735
(cherry picked from commit 37e9907a176dad6843819b1bec4946c3aecc4548)
(cherry picked from commit 2f2736ebb267c757ad77fcf25ee0aaeefab2a09d)
(cherry picked from commit 27caafe3daa552663719954f2cd6713dd4493178)

revisions:
[{'created': '2020-05-11 19:45:08.000000000', 'message': 'Add support for object replication handoffs_first

In extreme cases of object rebalance or node failure, swift environments
with millions of objects may have a hard time with objects landing in
handoff or misplaced partitions and the operator of the cloud may need
to prioritize migrating data in handoff partitions back to primary
partitions over the 3 primary partitions replicating amongst each other.

To allow for this, the object-server.conf [object-replicator]
configuration can have handoffs_first set to True which will force
the object-replicators to focus on handoff partitions before syncing
primary partitions for any given object partition.

Change-Id: I8b44c287567a0e6d634def0b13baf0fe4ad4aa7b
Closes-Bug: 1878087
'}]
commit_message:
Add support for object replication handoffs_first

In extreme cases of object rebalance or node failure, swift environments
with millions of objects may have a hard time with objects landing in
handoff or misplaced partitions and the operator of the cloud may need
to prioritize migrating data in handoff partitions back to primary
partitions over the 3 primary partitions replicating amongst each other.

To allow for this, the object-server.conf [object-replicator]
configuration can have handoffs_first set to True which will force
the object-replicators to focus on handoff partitions before syncing
primary partitions for any given object partition.

Change-Id: I8b44c287567a0e6d634def0b13baf0fe4ad4aa7b
Closes-Bug: 1878087

commit_message:
Introducing tripleo_delegate_to on ceph health validation

The purpose of this change is to fix the upgrade scenario
without breaking the existing validation for the
deployment phase.  During the upgrade from queens, the
default 'container_cli' is podman in the undercloud (which
is updated), but it's still docker in the overcloud and this
let the validation playbook to fail because we're computing
this fact starting from inventory_hostname that still points
to the undercloud.  This issue can be solved by removing the
delegation directive from tht and rely on tripleo delegate
wrapper.
This should be enough to access the overcloud (ceph_mon)
variables, setting the right fact.

Closes-Bug: #1871380
Change-Id: I46c4fbe0ef7b281d77bff82483eb0b48b4570bb3
(cherry picked from commit 3baced6e89d4d3af7d2190f4c587a4ee05f5977a)

I'm not sure how I feel about us hosting code for deploying a non-open source project..."}, {'account_id': 935, 'date': '2020-04-28 16:05:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hi Mohammed

I had some of the same reservations when I put this governance proposal forward but I decided it needed testing.

Here are some other points that we might want to consider:

We have numerous other code bases under OpenStack/OpenDev that integrate OpenStack with storage, networking and compute solutions which are not free or open source.

The deployment tooling (charms) is free software licensed under Apache-2.0 as required by OpenStack.'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2020-04-30 06:51:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Code-Review'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2020-05-04 09:33:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

There might be some precedent in other deployment tools:

openstack/ansible-role-atos-hsm
openstack/ansible-role-thales-hsm
openstack/openstack-ansible-galera_client

If I'm not mistaken, at least some of those are not open source?"}, {'account_id': 17068, 'date': '2020-05-07 11:23:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

> There might be some precedent in other deployment tools:
 > 
 > openstack/ansible-role-atos-hsm
 > openstack/ansible-role-thales-hsm
 > openstack/openstack-ansible-galera_client
 > 
 > If I'm not mistaken, at least some of those are not open source?

The deployment tooling is licensed under our usual license, so I don't see it as a problem.

What's behind the scenes can be discussed. HSMs are very particular and the galera_client role is behind the scenes here just mysql licensed client, open source. That role could even simply be using mariadb binaries now. So I don't see this as a problem."}, {'account_id': 17068, 'date': '2020-05-07 11:25:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Rollcall-Vote+1

> Hi Mohammed
 > 
 > I had some of the same reservations when I put this governance
 > proposal forward but I decided it needed testing.
 > 
 > Here are some other points that we might want to consider:
 > 
 > We have numerous other code bases under OpenStack/OpenDev that
 > integrate OpenStack with storage, networking and compute solutions
 > which are not free or open source.
 > 
 > The deployment tooling (charms) is free software licensed under
 > Apache-2.0 as required by OpenStack.

I agree with James here. Better build it in the open and the community at large, than just hiding it in some dark place, preventing the contributors to step up further. The deployment tooling here follows our license, so I don't see a reason to alienate those devs."}, {'account_id': 12404, 'date': '2020-05-07 13:34:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Rollcall-Vote+1

from my understand of point, it's OpenStack Charms we mark as Open source, as long as TrilioVault not become a dependency, I do fine with have (open source) scripts for non-open source. But however, still need to be careful with what we gonna test in CI."}, {'account_id': 935, 'date': '2020-05-07 13:46:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

with regards to CI - actual functional testing of TrilioVault as deployed by the new charms will be undertaken in a 3rd party CI operated by Canonical.

Only unit and lint tests will be done on opendev infra.'}, {'account_id': 1004, 'date': '2020-05-10 17:40:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

if other TC members feel this is ok, they should vote on it.

the atos-hsm and thales-hsm are indeed similar to an extent.  galera_client i disagree because it's open source so it's not deploying any binary bits that we don't know

i guess my question is: would we be okay with hosting, say, a "vmware deployment tool".  again, other TC members can vote on this and my -1 doesn't mean it won't merge.'}, {'account_id': 8556, 'date': '2020-05-11 16:27:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Rollcall-Vote+1

I am ok with this. We cannot 100% de-integrate the opensource with non-open source things. There are already non-open source backends for many services which are/can be tested with 3rd party CI.'}, {'account_id': 7353, 'date': '2020-05-11 16:32:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Rollcall-Vote+1

I'm OK with this. From the point of a deployment tool, this seems perfectly within their purview to provide."}, {'account_id': 7198, 'date': '2020-05-11 16:36:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Rollcall-Vote+1

There are many cases in the storage realm where the technology being integrated is not open, but the integration to OpenStack is open.  So, I think there is precedent here.'}, {'account_id': 1004, 'date': '2020-05-11 18:51:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 13995, 'date': '2020-05-11 19:02:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Rollcall-Vote+1'}]

commit_message:
Infrastructure project team is now the TaCT SIG

Move remaining repositories under the Infrastructure project team
to the Testing and Collaboration Tools SIG.

Technically those repositories are not 'retired' so I did not list
them in legacy.yaml (following the precedent for repositories
previously-owned by Infrastructure and now under the Opendev project).

This change breaks a link to the "community sysadmins" investment
opportunity of 2018/2019, so I apply a quick workaround there.

Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/721619
Change-Id: I7da9a2060e6cb86fbea0e64a87afa05d46b0a2eb

commit_message:
Add ansible role for managing Luna SA HSM

This patch adds a new ansible role used to manage client software
for the Gemalto Luna SA Hardware Security Module (HSM).  This role
is used in TripleO to install HSM client software on Controller nodes
to enable the PCKS#11 backend for Barbican.

Change-Id: Ifb1c1f3ac87caf93d8e1d673b4c07753ca72fe93
Depends-On: Id694007e7da55f92952b1f55474a7f87bfdb3339

commit_message:
Fix: API returns 503 if one of the store is mis-configured

If user mis-configures one of the multiple stores defined in glance-api
configuratio file, then service returns 503 for all API requests.

Made provision to exclude faulty store and resume service normally
to function wiht other configured stores.

Closes-Bug: #1875281
Change-Id: I685a0ecbfba7cf7dbce3fd2eb84f97bd8ffbfcf3
(cherry picked from commit 98b9091129e78d03dc5b97bd1503063499f166d5)
(cherry picked from commit 17b66ab6a50f8dda28fc2f4c02489bb5ba4241e3)
